Sorry, I should have been more specific, I was looking through the issues just for context. This is currently the ApplyToTest method in the nunit source on the dev branch

```
        public override void ApplyToTest(Test test)
        {
            // Adjust property to include ParallelScope.Self if a fixture has ParallelScope.Fixtures on it
            if (test is TestFixture && _scope.HasFlag(ParallelScope.Fixtures))
                Properties.Set(PropertyNames.ParallelScope, _scope | ParallelScope.Self);

            base.ApplyToTest(test);

            if (test.RunState == RunState.NotRunnable)
                return;

            if (_scope.HasFlag(ParallelScope.Self) && _scope.HasFlag(ParallelScope.None))
                test.MakeInvalid("Test may not be both parallel and non-parallel");

            if (test is TestMethod && _scope.HasFlag(ParallelScope.ContextMask))
                test.MakeInvalid("ParallelScope of a test method may not specify Children or Fixtures");
        }
```

Everything after the first `if` statement that changed in 3.8 the method has not been changed since 3.7. I just tested on the 3.8 dev myget package, and the tests still run and are not invalidated. From the bottom 2 `if` statements, it would imply that the tests should be made invalid and ignored. 

Sorry that was my bad for using `ParallelScope.None`, I realize it is better to use `NonParallelizable`. I wasn't trying to suggest I was using it, I was trying to refer to its actual functionality, and the fact that using it can dramatically slow down a test run.

I do have the fixtures marked as `ParallelScope.Self`, the functionality that would be desired is that there is some way for a particular one of those test in that fixture to only be run one at a time.
 
I realize one way around this would be to put that particular test in a fixture of its own and have `ParallelScope.Fixtures` above it in the tree so that single test would one one at a time, but it would be nice to have flexibility within a single fixture to avoid splitting a fixture.

Regarding invalidating the test, please post some code that you believe should have been marked invalid but was not. As indicated, if you have a method with both ParallelScope.None and ParallelScope.Self, then it should be marked invalid. Same thing for a test case with either Children or Fixtures, since a test case can't contain any child tests.

Again... assuming you have a fixture containing some tests that should run in parallel and some that should not, you can do one of two things...

```C#
[Parallelizable(ParallelScope.Children)] // Or any other scope that excludes children
public class TestFixture
{
    // Mark non-parallelizable methods with [NonParallelizable]
}

[NonParallelizable] // or anyother attribute that doesn't include Children
public class AnotherFixture
{
    // Mark parallelizable tests with [Parallelizable]
}
```

If I'm misunderstanding you, please post some code!

Here is a sample fixture I used to test this,
```
    [TestFixture]
    [TestFixtureSource(nameof(Params))]
    [Parallelizable]
    public class UnitTest2
    {
        private static object[] Params = {
            new object[] { "test 1" },
            new object[] { "test 2" }
        };
        public UnitTest2(string test)
        {
        }

        [Test]
        [NonParallelizable]
        [Parallelizable(ParallelScope.Self)]
        public void NUnitTest1()
        {
            Thread.Sleep(5000);
        }

        [Test]
        [Parallelizable(ParallelScope.Fixtures)]
        public void NUnitTest2()
        {
            Thread.Sleep(5000);
        }
    }
```

